    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Fast Check-In for Flights</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from David Kanon contrasts long lines at airports in United States to system in London, where there are check-in counters for all major airlines at train stations (May 8 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>After reading your article about long airport lines (front page, May 8), a recent travel experience came to mind. In Paddington Station, the train station in London, there is a full check-in counter for all major airlines where one can receive one's boarding pass and check luggage at any time during the day of the flight. One can show up at the gate a few minutes before the flight, freeing up valuable time.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>After reading your article about long airport lines (front page, May 8), a recent travel experience came to mind. In Paddington Station, the train station in London, there is a full check-in counter for all major airlines where one can receive one's boarding pass and check luggage at any time during the day of the flight. One can show up at the gate a few minutes before the flight, freeing up valuable time.</p>
        <p>In fact, the longest wait I encountered on my trip was at security. Thanks to the easy check-in, my last day in London was more enjoyable because I did not have to worry about getting to the airport hours in advance. If major American cities developed a central service like the one mentioned, perhaps airport lines could be avoided.</p>
        <p>DAVID  KANON  New York, May 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
